\section{Relations between ${\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G)$ and ${\gamma_{\rm gr}}(G)$}
\label{sec:relations}

Let $S=(v_1,\ldots,v_k)$ be a sequence of distinct vertices of a graph $G$ and $\widehat{S}$ the corresponding set of vertices.
This sequence $S$ is called a \emph{legal (closed neighborhood) sequence}
if

nexttext:
\end{prop}
{\noindent\textbf{Proof. }}
Let $S=(v_1,\ldots, v_t)$ be a Grundy transversal sequence in ${\cal H}$, and let $(E_1,\ldots,E_t)$ be a legal sequence of edges in ${\cal H}$ such that $E_i$ was hit by $v_i$ (i.e. $v_i\in E_i$) but was not
hit by the vertices that precede $v_i$ in $S$. We claim that the sequence $S'$ of these edges
in reverse order, that is $S'=(E_t,\ldots,E_1)$, is a Grundy covering sequence. Indeed, if $E_i$ is an arbitrary edge in this sequence, then $v_i\in E_i$, but $v_i\notin E_j$ for $j>i$, because in the transversal sequence $S$ the set $E_j$ was hit for the first time only later, by the vertex $v_j$. Hence, $S'$ is an edge covering sequence, and ${\rho_{\rm gr}}({\cal H})\ge t={\tau_{\rm gr}}({\cal H})$.

For the converse the same idea can be used. Note that if $S=(E_1,\ldots,E_u)$ is a Grundy covering sequence of ${\cal H}$, and $v_i$ is a vertex that is in $E_i$
but is not in $E_1\cup\cdots\cup E_{i-1}$ (for each $i$), then the sequence $S'=(v_u,\ldots,v_1)$ is a legal transversal sequence. This implies ${\tau_{\rm gr}}({\cal H})\ge u={\rho_{\rm gr}}({\cal H})$.
{$\Box$}
\medskip

From Proposition~\ref{p:rho-tau}, and the fact that the Grundy total domination number of the incidence graph of ${\cal H}$ coincides with ${\tau_{\rm gr}}({\cal H})+{\rho_{\rm gr}}({\cal H})$ we derive the following result.

\begin{thm}
If ${\cal H}$ is a hypergraph and $G$ the incidence graph of ${\cal H}$, then ${\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G)=2{\rho_{\rm gr}}({\cal H})$.
\end{thm}

Since the reduction from a hypergraph to its incidence graph (which is bipartite) is efficiently computable,
it follows that {\sc Grundy Total Domination Number} is NP-hard even in bipartite graphs.

\begin{cor}
{\sc Grundy Total Domination Number} is NP-complete, even when restricted to bipartite graphs.
\end{cor}



\section{Open Problems}

We conclude with an open question and several open problems that we have yet to settle. By Observation~\ref{ob:bip}, there is no constant $c > 0$ such that ${\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G) \ge c|V(G)|$ for every bipartite graph $G$ that is open twin-free. However, in our constructions every vertex belongs to a $4$-cycle. We pose the following question.

\begin{quest}
Does there exist a positive constant $c$ such that ${\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G) \ge c|V(G)|$ for every bipartite graph $G$ with no $4$-cycles and with minimum degree at least~$2$?
\end{quest}

By Proposition~\ref{p:deg}, if $G$ is a graph of order~$n$, then ${\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G) \le n - \delta(G) + 1$. We have yet to characterize the graphs achieving equality in this upper bound.

\begin{prob}
Characterize the graphs $G$ of order~$n$ for which ${\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G) = n - \delta(G) + 1$.
\end{prob}



\begin{prob}
Find an efficient algorithm to compute the Grundy total domination number for trees.
\end{prob}

By Corollary~\ref{cor:cubic}, if $G \ne K_{3,3}$ is a connected cubic graph of order~$n$, then ${\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G) \ge \frac{1}{2}n$. We observed that this bound is achievable.

\begin{prob}
Characterize the connected cubic graphs $G \ne K_{3,3}$ of order~$n$ for which ${\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G) = \frac{1}{2}n$.
\end{prob}

By Corollary~\ref{cor:4reg}, if $G \ne K_{4,4}$ is a connected $4$-regular graph of order~$n$, then ${\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G) \ge \frac{1}{3}n$. We observed that this bound is achievable.

\begin{prob}
Characterize the connected $4$-regular graphs $G \ne K_{4,4}$ of order~$n$ for which ${\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G) = \frac{1}{3}n$.
\end{prob}

By Observation~\ref{chain}, for every graph $G$, $\gamma_t(G) \le {\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G)$. By Theorem~\ref{thm:multi}, the graphs $G$ for which ${\gamma_t}(G) = {\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G) = 2$ are precisely the complete multipartite graphs. By Theorem~\ref{thm:Tdom3}, there is no graph $G$ satisfying ${\gamma_t}(G) = {\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G) = 3$. By Theorem~\ref{ob:gt4}, there are infinitely many connected graphs $G$ with ${\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G) = {\gamma_t}(G) = 4$. It remains an open problem to characterize the graphs $G$ for which ${\gamma_t}(G) = {\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G) = k$ when $k \ge 4$.



\begin{prob}
Characterize the graphs $G$ such that ${\gamma_t}(G) = {\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G) = k$ for $k \ge 4$.
\end{prob}

By Theorem~\ref{thm:interpolation}, if $G$ is a graph, then ${\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G)\le 2{\gamma_{\rm gr}}(G)$, and the class of complete graphs, $K_n$ with $n \ge 2$, achieve equality in this bound. However, it remains an open problem to characterize the extremal graphs.

\begin{prob}
Characterize the graphs $G$ for which ${\gamma_{\rm gr}^t}(G)= 2{\gamma_{\rm gr}}(G)$.
\end{prob}

